WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:03.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:16.300 --> 00:00:19.740
&gt;&gt; Guha Shankar: Good evening,
afternoon, thank you all so much

00:00:19.740 --> 00:00:22.220
for coming to this
wonderful session.

00:00:22.220 --> 00:00:25.470
It's been a long time in the
making for a number of us here.

00:00:25.470 --> 00:00:30.220
Great to see old and familiar
faces, some new ones as well,

00:00:30.220 --> 00:00:35.270
and it promises to be a really
exciting afternoon...as exciting

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:37.630
as online presentations can be.

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:42.210
One housekeeping note
- if you wouldn't mind,

00:00:42.210 --> 00:00:44.140
turning off your cell phones?

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:47.400
Turn off your cell phones
because we care and,

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:50.140
they also interfere with the
wireless equipment in the room.

00:00:50.140 --> 00:00:53.680
And I'm going to keep my remarks
[short], basically by saying

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:55.930
that I'm here to
essentially hurry people on

00:00:55.930 --> 00:00:57.330
and off the stage
- or not hurry -

00:00:57.330 --> 00:01:00.620
gently move people along
and introduce people.

00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:04.820
And in doing so, let me
introduce my boss, the director

00:01:04.820 --> 00:01:09.020
of the American Folklife Center,
my boss, Dr. Betsy Peterson.

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:14.670
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Peterson:
Thank you, Guha.

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:18.660
As he said, I am Betsy Peterson
- I think I am anyway And I want

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:21.310
to welcome everyone today.

00:01:21.310 --> 00:01:25.980
This has been an exciting and
a long time coming to get,

00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:29.680
get all of us in the same room
so we can begin to reflect

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:32.200
and talk about what this
whole process has been

00:01:32.200 --> 00:01:34.420
in the last couple of years.

00:01:34.420 --> 00:01:37.490
But, let me step back
a minute and sort

00:01:37.490 --> 00:01:41.000
of go back a little further and
tell you a little bit about AFC

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.780
and what AFC has done
in terms of working

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:49.380
with Native American
collections and communities.

00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:52.280
The American Folklife Center
has long been involved

00:01:52.280 --> 00:01:55.720
in initiatives to jointly
engage federal repositories

00:01:55.720 --> 00:02:00.340
and Native American community
members in curating, preserving,

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:03.820
and providing access to
their own cultural heritage,

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:07.630
whether the focus was on analog
materials, on wax cylinders,

00:02:07.630 --> 00:02:11.450
or whether it is on
emerging digital formats.

00:02:11.450 --> 00:02:15.440
Notably, the Library was the
very first federal institution

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:18.560
to actively engage
in the repatriation

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:22.400
of recorded cultural heritage
to indigenous communities

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:23.770
to actively -- Whoops.

00:02:23.770 --> 00:02:27.720
I just missed a line
there...In the repatriation

00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:32.160
of recorded cultural heritage to
indigenous communities by means

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:37.790
of the Federal Cylinder Project,
which was initiated in 1979.

00:02:37.790 --> 00:02:41.130
And Judith Gray is one of
the individuals who was

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:43.980
on that illustrious
team at the time.

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:45.360
Through this program,

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:49.060
the Library coordinated a tape
preservation program focused

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:52.660
on fragile wax cylinders
housed in several public

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:56.590
and university repositories,
bringing them together.

00:02:56.590 --> 00:02:59.440
Subsequently, through
careful collaborative work

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.260
with community experts and
elders, we returned recordings

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:06.290
to over 100 communities
to assist

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:09.430
in community based
programs, for cultural

00:03:09.430 --> 00:03:13.460
and linguistic preservation
and dissemination.

00:03:13.460 --> 00:03:18.890
So, now let's jump ahead to
2018 and to the 2.0 version

00:03:18.890 --> 00:03:22.170
of the Federal Cylinder Project.

00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:24.410
This time around, we are working

00:03:24.410 --> 00:03:29.240
on digitizing these fragile wax
cylinders, but so much more -

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:34.030
thanks to all this
wonderful new technology

00:03:34.030 --> 00:03:38.130
that is making certain things
possible and really making,

00:03:38.130 --> 00:03:41.790
I think, the dream of
collaborative curation,

00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:46.170
much more possible, to
promote the ethical exchange

00:03:46.170 --> 00:03:47.550
of information.

00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:52.110
And it's also in part due
to the indefatigable -

00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:56.930
and I want to underline
that - team of Jane Anderson

00:03:56.930 --> 00:04:01.080
and Kim Christen, who
are piloting and -

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:05.170
and championing the Mukurtu
content management system

00:04:05.170 --> 00:04:09.780
and the Local [Contexts] and the
Traditional Knowledge labels,

00:04:09.780 --> 00:04:12.820
which they'll be able to tell
you a little bit more about.

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:17.600
I also want to thank our
esteemed guests and experts.

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:20.630
Donald Soctomah from
the Passamaquoddy tribe

00:04:20.630 --> 00:04:22.300
and Dwayne Tomah.

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:25.590
Welcome! And what
you're going to hear

00:04:25.590 --> 00:04:28.850
from us today is just
everyone talking a little bit

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:30.280
about what this process

00:04:30.280 --> 00:04:34.290
of collaborative curation
is all about, what it means

00:04:34.290 --> 00:04:37.140
to the different parties
involved, how they're doing,

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:42.030
what they're doing and where
we see things going - further.

00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:45.960
I also want to just give a
brief shout out to Gene DeAnna,

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:50.120
who is the former
head of Recorded Sound

00:04:50.120 --> 00:04:52.930
at Motion Picture, Broadcasting,
and Recorded Sound [division].

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:56.660
Gene was very instrumental
in working with us

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:01.500
to move the wax cylinders
out to the Culpepper facility

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:04.900
and really kind of jump starting
and pushing this project

00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:06.200
and getting it started.

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:07.500
So it's wonderful to see you.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:11.430
Glad you're here.

00:05:11.430 --> 00:05:14.050
And with that said, I think
you'll be hearing a little bit

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:18.030
more about the history and bits
and pieces of these projects

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:20.030
as we begin our conversation.

00:05:20.030 --> 00:05:24.740
And so I would just like
to welcome Donald Soctomah

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:28.430
to the podium, or you
may actually just sit

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:32.600
and probably talk from there.

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:36.100
Is that all right?

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:37.550
Ok... So thank you.

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:38.900
Donald.

00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:41.640
&gt;&gt; Donald Soctomah: Thank you.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:44.410
I'm happy to be here and
be part of the process

00:05:44.410 --> 00:05:47.070
on the, wax cylinders.

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:54.920
This truly is - ancestral voices
returning back to the tribe.

00:05:54.920 --> 00:06:03.380
It's so powerful to hear a voice
128 years ago of a grandfather,

00:06:03.380 --> 00:06:07.890
a great grandfather that
could be lost in time.

00:06:07.890 --> 00:06:11.820
But what's really powerful
is they're singing songs

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:19.570
and telling stories that haven't
been told, haven't been sung.

00:06:19.570 --> 00:06:22.940
We've spent two years?

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:28.290
almost three [laughter] and
every time I take the recordings

00:06:28.290 --> 00:06:33.770
to elderly in our
community to hear,

00:06:33.770 --> 00:06:36.750
I get different types
of reactions.

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:40.210
The first type of
reaction is emotional.

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:43.050
And I thought about that.

00:06:43.050 --> 00:06:47.070
What, you know, to me, this
is powerful, but I was trying

00:06:47.070 --> 00:06:50.650
to think of different reasons
for the strong emotion.

00:06:50.650 --> 00:06:57.780
And it - it came to me that the
language that's being spoken is

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:01.580
the same accent that the elders'
grandparents probably talked

00:07:01.580 --> 00:07:05.000
to them, the same
accent, the same words.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:06.300
It's so powerful.

00:07:06.300 --> 00:07:12.070
So, it takes them back a couple
generations and then the memory

00:07:12.070 --> 00:07:16.500
from the voices goes back
another couple of generations.

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:26.320
And, and the - the songs, the
war songs, the trading songs,

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:30.970
the stories that are on
these cylinders, they're...

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:34.440
they're just- just amazing,
because they're parts

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:37.040
of our history at
certain time periods.

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:44.100
The war song - you know,
if we think back into time,

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.530
the last big war
that the tribe was

00:07:46.530 --> 00:07:51.810
in was the American
Revolution in 1776.

00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:53.860
The chief at our
time, at that time,

00:07:53.860 --> 00:07:57.500
was Chief Francis
Joseph Neptune.

00:07:57.500 --> 00:08:02.360
So we were able to piece this
together, because, remember,

00:08:02.360 --> 00:08:05.220
wax cylinders are only
two to three minutes

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:10.400
and native songs can go for
15 to 20 minutes, you know.

00:08:10.400 --> 00:08:13.950
So we're getting just a
piece of the pie on that.

00:08:13.950 --> 00:08:18.940
So we have a little view back
into the American Revolution -

00:08:18.940 --> 00:08:24.480
a view from the eyes and
the voice of the ancestors.

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:29.070
It - that's so powerful,
you know.

00:08:29.070 --> 00:08:32.890
And one of the stories
talks about -

00:08:32.890 --> 00:08:35.780
talks about different
legends of the tribe

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:38.510
that have been passed on,

00:08:38.510 --> 00:08:41.180
that some of the stories
I've heard growing up,

00:08:41.180 --> 00:08:43.030
but I haven't heard
them complete

00:08:43.030 --> 00:08:45.880
like they are in
the wax cylinder.

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:49.630
It's... pretty powerful.

00:08:49.630 --> 00:08:53.130
We took the wax cylinders and
we sat with a group of elders -

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:57.960
I think the average age
was probably seventy-five

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:01.870
and Dwayne - Dwayne's the
youngest fluent speaker

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:04.480
in our tribe.

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:09.810
And, that's - that's
quite a comment,

00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:12.810
because the youngest
fluent speaker

00:09:12.810 --> 00:09:21.320
in our tribe...I can't remember
how old you are, but it's -

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:26.520
it's about fifty and
he's right there,

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:28.770
and everybody [else
is] above that age.

00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:32.100
It just - the fluency
rate keeps increasing.

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:36.570
And so right now I think it's
over the age of sixty-five,

00:09:36.570 --> 00:09:40.590
almost all the people in our
community over sixty-five,

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:43.680
I'd say ninety percent
are fluent speakers.

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:46.150
They were raised speaking
the language and they had

00:09:46.150 --> 00:09:48.590
that memory going
back into time.

00:09:48.590 --> 00:09:50.700
And then it just goes down-

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:53.500
percentage wise -to
our children today

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:57.640
that they hear words
here and there.

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:01.430
This- last three years
we were pretty lucky.

00:10:01.430 --> 00:10:04.130
We started a language immersion
school for children three

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:09.760
to five, and this is the
first batch of kids growing

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:14.500
up hearing the language,
so it's bringing that back.

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:19.200
So, we -we took the
cylinders to the teachers,

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:25.120
to the master speakers and the
elders, and they sat in a circle

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:28.860
and we kept trying to make
the words out because some

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:33.550
of the songs are pretty -
pretty hard to understand -

00:10:33.550 --> 00:10:35.540
because of the scratches,

00:10:35.540 --> 00:10:38.810
but some of the songs are
[audible and] you can hear them

00:10:38.810 --> 00:10:44.430
and you can feel the
emotion from the singer.

00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:50.640
And we had some debate on some
of the words and the meaning,

00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:55.220
because languages
over time changes.

00:10:55.220 --> 00:10:59.840
And - the English language
I know has changed,

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:03.430
because I've tried to read
some old English books

00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:06.210
and it's almost impossible
[laughter].

00:11:06.210 --> 00:11:10.740
But even with Passamaquoddy, our
language has changed over time

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:12.140
in the last hundred years.

00:11:12.140 --> 00:11:13.610
It's changed.

00:11:13.610 --> 00:11:16.250
The words have gotten
a little bit shorter -

00:11:16.250 --> 00:11:20.630
and some of the words
are out of use because -

00:11:20.630 --> 00:11:26.270
we don't have these stories
of legendary creatures

00:11:26.270 --> 00:11:29.640
like the Apotmakin You don't
hear that word very much.

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:32.250
It's a sea serpent, so
you don't hear the legend

00:11:32.250 --> 00:11:36.670
of the sea serpent very much,
so it sort of gets out of use,

00:11:36.670 --> 00:11:39.990
but these wax cylinders
are bringing them back,

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:43.690
bringing them back into
use, bringing the songs

00:11:43.690 --> 00:11:47.760
that the singers
haven't heard before.

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:50.910
[There are] a couple of
the songs we still use

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:57.340
in our Indian Day ceremonies,
but I - I can say that some

00:11:57.340 --> 00:12:00.270
of them I've never heard
before [and] I don't think any

00:12:00.270 --> 00:12:03.980
of the master speakers in our
community have heard before.

00:12:03.980 --> 00:12:07.320
So it's bringing a
gift back to the tribe.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:10.570
And we're - we're at a
critical moment in our tribe

00:12:10.570 --> 00:12:15.260
where language fluency
is - every year it goes

00:12:15.260 --> 00:12:18.200
down a whole percentage point.

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:21.990
So last time I was here, it
was - we were at ten per cent

00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:25.000
of our population
were fluent speakers.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.660
Now it's probably down to eight
percent because the elders,

00:12:28.660 --> 00:12:33.560
every elder - that's a
fluent speaker right there.

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:36.380
So this comes at
an important time.

00:12:36.380 --> 00:12:43.640
It's giving some of us, a sort
of a shot in the arm of energy,

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:46.280
[and we're] saying, "Okay,
this is what we're going to do.

00:12:46.280 --> 00:12:47.750
We're going to bring
this forward."

00:12:47.750 --> 00:12:51.630
And - and it energizes
other people,

00:12:51.630 --> 00:12:56.080
it energizes the
singers in our community.

00:12:56.080 --> 00:13:00.000
I've had so many requests
from tribal - tribal singers

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.390
in our community - because they
want to hear the wax cylinders

00:13:03.390 --> 00:13:05.920
and they want to sing the songs.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:12.930
So to me, this is a
great project and it's

00:13:12.930 --> 00:13:21.230
so much work ahead and so
much work has been done and -

00:13:21.230 --> 00:13:26.150
the Mukurtu site is one way.

00:13:26.150 --> 00:13:30.330
We put this all together onto
a Mukurtu site and Jane's going

00:13:30.330 --> 00:13:34.040
to talk about [that], then Kim's
going to talk about that later,

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:38.600
but for us it gives us
a little bit of control

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:43.550
on our cultural films,
music books,

00:13:43.550 --> 00:13:47.860
and the tribe's able to...have
a little bit of control

00:13:47.860 --> 00:13:51.310
on our stuff that
we've never had before.

00:13:51.310 --> 00:13:55.130
And that's, that's pretty
powerful on its own.

00:13:55.130 --> 00:14:00.360
Everybody else has had
control over our songs,

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:07.410
over our stories [but]
this puts it back on to us.

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:11.110
And to me that's the
way it should be,

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:14.310
because our ancestors
shared the stories.

00:14:14.310 --> 00:14:19.220
They didn't give the stories to
anybody, but they shared them.

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:22.840
And then for the tribe -
there's a tribe in Canada,

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:28.930
it's one of our neighbors,
they- they shared the stories

00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:32.830
with a writer in the
mid-eighteen hundreds

00:14:32.830 --> 00:14:36.080
and this writer said, "I'm
just going to document this

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:39.630
and I'm going to return
this back to the tribe."

00:14:39.630 --> 00:14:42.280
Well, before he completed
[it], he passed on,

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:46.030
and his family got a
hold of the stories

00:14:46.030 --> 00:14:49.870
and the family told
the tribe that -

00:14:49.870 --> 00:14:54.580
that they have the copyright,
those are their stories,

00:14:54.580 --> 00:14:57.090
and they [the tribe] were
being threatened to go to court

00:14:57.090 --> 00:15:02.300
because those were the
writer's stories - copyrighted.

00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:05.230
So the tribe was in
a turmoil, you know,

00:15:05.230 --> 00:15:09.380
these are ours ...how can
anyone claim these stories?!

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:15.770
So - we're learning a lot
through this whole process,

00:15:15.770 --> 00:15:22.220
especially with expertise that
helps us understand [the law].

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:28.130
Personally, I know what rights,
you know, my ancestors story,

00:15:28.130 --> 00:15:32.940
my ancestors song belongs
to the Passamaquoddy tribe.

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:36.960
But the way laws
are today, you know,

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:42.330
it just makes everything
a little bit harder.

00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:46.580
So - I'm grateful for being
here for the opportunity to work

00:15:46.580 --> 00:15:52.700
with all these wonderful people,
for the Library of Congress and,

00:15:52.700 --> 00:15:57.540
and for ones in the
back there that -

00:15:57.540 --> 00:16:00.610
that have been working
just as hard.

00:16:00.610 --> 00:16:07.880
It's - it, it takes a
team to make things work.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:11.060
And that's what I see
here - a good team.

00:16:11.060 --> 00:16:14.310
I want to thank you.

00:16:14.310 --> 00:16:21.310
&gt;&gt; Guha Shankar:
Thank you very much.

00:16:21.310 --> 00:16:22.610
Donald.

00:16:22.610 --> 00:16:24.380
&gt;&gt; Donald Soctomah:
We're going to play the-

00:16:24.380 --> 00:16:27.650
what was called a
trading song - when,

00:16:27.650 --> 00:16:29.660
when Fewkes put the
titles together,

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:32.680
he just put a basic title on it.

00:16:32.680 --> 00:16:47.100
I don't think he wanted to go
into detail, because his job was

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:56.570
to record and so things were
just labeled as "trading song"

00:16:56.570 --> 00:17:02.870
or "war song one," "war song
two" or "war song three,"

00:17:02.870 --> 00:17:07.080
but there's different
- categories of trade,

00:17:07.080 --> 00:17:10.390
different types of trading.

00:17:10.390 --> 00:17:17.420
In our- our history that's been
written, the tribes are known

00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:19.600
for their trading skills.

00:17:19.600 --> 00:17:22.190
When the explorers came over
[from Europe] in their journals,

00:17:22.190 --> 00:17:27.300
they said, "Well, these guys
know how to deal in a trade.

00:17:27.300 --> 00:17:33.750
I wanted to trade this - cook
pan for one beaver skin -

00:17:33.750 --> 00:17:41.130
but I ended up giving two
pots for the one beaver skin!"

00:17:41.130 --> 00:17:43.670
[laughter] So the tribe was well
known for its trading skills

00:17:43.670 --> 00:17:45.860
and that's a part of survival.

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:50.340
So our tribe has - what I've
seen - three trading songs

00:17:50.340 --> 00:17:53.310
over time, and one's
interesting -

00:17:53.310 --> 00:17:55.680
its called a "clown
trading song.".

00:17:55.680 --> 00:18:00.040
And the clown trading
song is ...wintertime -

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:02.910
everybody's in the
wigwam and you're sitting

00:18:02.910 --> 00:18:07.750
around the fire staying
warm, and you sort of,

00:18:07.750 --> 00:18:10.650
you're preparing the
kids for the big trade.

00:18:10.650 --> 00:18:12.970
So you're making fun of
the trader, you know,

00:18:12.970 --> 00:18:15.560
the one that's going to come
in: "Oh, he's coming in,

00:18:15.560 --> 00:18:18.460
he's coming in with baggy
clothes, he's coming in."

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:24.040
And then there's the
other type of trade, the -

00:18:24.040 --> 00:18:30.390
the trade where you're going
- trading the good for a good

00:18:30.390 --> 00:18:33.290
at equal, equal par
and everything.

00:18:33.290 --> 00:18:38.780
So - what we're going to
play here is the Trading Song

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:44.130
and this is the one that
the children - picked up.

00:18:44.130 --> 00:18:51.650
We played it at a - at a - well,
one of the - we had the group

00:18:51.650 --> 00:18:56.400
of immersion children that
were learning the language

00:18:56.400 --> 00:19:00.800
and they sat at the table and
the teacher sat at the table -

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:03.230
the teachers are
master speakers.

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:05.030
So when...

00:19:05.030 --> 00:19:07.580
one teacher heard that,
it started coming back

00:19:07.580 --> 00:19:12.580
to her she remembers hearing
that when she was a young girl.

00:19:15.510 --> 00:19:47.760
[Song from Passamaquoddy
Collection: The Trading Song"

00:19:47.760 --> 00:20:20.000
by Newell Josephs, 1890]

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:23.290
&gt;&gt; So we worked on this
song for a couple months.

00:20:23.290 --> 00:20:28.130
It's a short song, but I
worked with Wayne Newell

00:20:28.130 --> 00:20:32.590
on this song and he...

00:20:32.590 --> 00:20:37.210
we went over word by word, just
stopping the music and going

00:20:37.210 --> 00:20:44.270
through and he's in his
late eighties maybe,

00:20:44.270 --> 00:20:47.460
and he's never heard
that song before.

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:53.290
So it, it took us a while for
him to put the words together.

00:20:53.290 --> 00:21:02.890
And - he was amazed,
he was really amazed.

00:21:02.890 --> 00:21:09.360
So this song was done by
Peter...Peter Selmore.

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:14.190
So I, I tried to do a little bio
on Peter Selmore, but one thing

00:21:14.190 --> 00:21:20.480
about our tribe - we have
sort of like a name game.

00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:26.850
The traditional names
today - aren't really -

00:21:26.850 --> 00:21:34.490
it's not our custom, but when
- when, a father has a son,

00:21:34.490 --> 00:21:39.950
they'll call him Little
Joseph, so he'll be - Josap,

00:21:39.950 --> 00:21:44.790
they'll say Little Joseph,
you know, in English,

00:21:44.790 --> 00:21:49.500
they'll call him that
and then - then his,

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:54.420
his father's last name
becomes the son's first name,

00:21:54.420 --> 00:21:58.200
so you're trying to
follow this on a census.

00:21:58.200 --> 00:22:03.650
And then his son takes
his father's last name

00:22:03.650 --> 00:22:06.590
as his first name, so it's
switching back and forth.

00:22:06.590 --> 00:22:09.660
And then somewhere in
the mix there'll be,

00:22:09.660 --> 00:22:14.250
maybe a nickname
becomes a first name.

00:22:14.250 --> 00:22:18.440
So I've come across
..three Peter Selmore,

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:23.830
and his nickname was
kci-kakak, which,

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:26.590
which means the Crow, the Raven.

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:36.240
So, his father -- I found
last night in a document,

00:22:36.240 --> 00:22:39.940
and his father couldn't
speak English,

00:22:39.940 --> 00:22:42.210
he refused to speak French.

00:22:42.210 --> 00:22:44.690
So he only spoke Passamaquoddy,

00:22:44.690 --> 00:22:46.380
because French was
a second language

00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:49.320
in the eighteen hundreds
of the tribe.

00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:55.470
And then English sort of took
over in the nineteen hundreds.

00:22:55.470 --> 00:22:58.770
So he had a brother named
Peter Selmore, well,

00:22:58.770 --> 00:23:03.500
a cousin that also took the
name, so finding the birth date

00:23:03.500 --> 00:23:07.660
in the census material is
usually - it's never right on -

00:23:07.660 --> 00:23:12.800
from the 1860 census
to the 1880 census.

00:23:12.800 --> 00:23:15.310
And then in the middle we
have the church census,

00:23:15.310 --> 00:23:18.060
the baptismals and marriages.

00:23:18.060 --> 00:23:21.790
So everything, the years
might be off one or two.

00:23:21.790 --> 00:23:28.390
And, then Noel Joseph, the
other singer, his name I found

00:23:28.390 --> 00:23:36.140
on the 1880 census, three Noel
Josephs and tracking them back

00:23:36.140 --> 00:23:40.070
