once you get into the project

00:32:57.840 --> 00:32:59.140
and you look at the ways

00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:01.300
in which communities are
defining what attribution is

00:33:01.300 --> 00:33:05.130
for them, what outreach
means for that community,

00:33:05.130 --> 00:33:08.170
you really see not only
the different contours

00:33:08.170 --> 00:33:10.700
of how we want to think
about sharing information,

00:33:10.700 --> 00:33:15.420
but that every community has
their own way of doing that.

00:33:15.420 --> 00:33:17.970
So, one of the labels, and I'll
just give you this quick example

00:33:17.970 --> 00:33:20.250
of the attribution label,
because it is the label

00:33:20.250 --> 00:33:22.090
that every community
chooses to use

00:33:22.090 --> 00:33:24.820
because the attribution
is what has been missing

00:33:24.820 --> 00:33:26.120
from the record.

00:33:26.120 --> 00:33:29.390
And in this sense, what
we did with this project,

00:33:29.390 --> 00:33:31.340
the particular kind
of a pivot point,

00:33:31.340 --> 00:33:33.770
is that the icon
itself remains the same.

00:33:33.770 --> 00:33:36.200
That's why you've been able
to see the icon in the Library

00:33:36.200 --> 00:33:39.650
of Congress record, but the
text and the description

00:33:39.650 --> 00:33:42.940
of what attribution means is
where every community is able

00:33:42.940 --> 00:33:45.880
to assert their own sovereignty
around what that means for them,

00:33:45.880 --> 00:33:48.770
including translating it
into their own language,

00:33:48.770 --> 00:33:50.830
which is what the
Passamaquoddy have done.

00:33:50.830 --> 00:33:54.830
The Passamaquoddy have
three labels that they chose

00:33:54.830 --> 00:33:57.150
for these particular
sound recordings.

00:33:57.150 --> 00:33:59.630
We have the non-commercial
label,

00:33:59.630 --> 00:34:01.540
we have the outreach label,
and we have, of course,

00:34:01.540 --> 00:34:03.440
we have the attribution label.

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:07.100
So when we - in 2016,

00:34:07.100 --> 00:34:10.140
we repatriated the
thirty-one digital files

00:34:10.140 --> 00:34:14.290
to the Passamaquoddy nation...to
the elders and to the children

00:34:14.290 --> 00:34:15.740
from the communities,
and we left them there

00:34:15.740 --> 00:34:17.040
with no strings attached.

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:19.770
And then since 2016,
I've been doing a lot

00:34:19.770 --> 00:34:21.070
of travel up to Passamaquoddy.

00:34:21.070 --> 00:34:24.430
Donald's been creating enormous
amounts of listening circles,

00:34:24.430 --> 00:34:27.240
just trying to hear
what's on these recordings.

00:34:27.240 --> 00:34:29.210
And so we're dealing
with two minutes of sound

00:34:29.210 --> 00:34:33.280
for one recording and for
a while were just working

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:34.750
on one recording.

00:34:34.750 --> 00:34:37.370
It took nearly a year...

00:34:37.370 --> 00:34:40.290
and we were playing
it again and again,

00:34:40.290 --> 00:34:44.230
stopping it every twenty seconds
to see what could be heard

00:34:44.230 --> 00:34:45.530
or what couldn't be heard.

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:48.620
And it was enormous
amounts of work!

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:51.000
And the concentration
that was needed to do

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:52.990
that over several days.

00:34:52.990 --> 00:34:56.370
And that kind of process,
which has been, you know,

00:34:56.370 --> 00:34:59.420
since we began it, we've
kind of streamlined it

00:34:59.420 --> 00:35:00.720
in a different kind of way.

00:35:00.720 --> 00:35:03.680
And now we have, you know, we
now have three records that are

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:05.050
in the Library of Congress.

00:35:05.050 --> 00:35:06.620
They happened really quickly.

00:35:06.620 --> 00:35:09.470
We have another four that we're
working on with Passamaquoddy

00:35:09.470 --> 00:35:10.890
that are going to be
incorporated into the Library

00:35:10.890 --> 00:35:12.190
of Congress [records].

00:35:12.190 --> 00:35:14.900
So the kind of...we've worked
out a process that has sped

00:35:14.900 --> 00:35:19.180
up a little bit, this work
of sharing the information

00:35:19.180 --> 00:35:20.820
that Passamaquoddy have
been determining is

00:35:20.820 --> 00:35:22.580
on these cylinders.

00:35:22.580 --> 00:35:24.300
So I want to show you a...

00:35:24.300 --> 00:35:28.230
just an example, of what
this process looks like.

00:35:28.230 --> 00:35:31.410
This is Molly Neptune
Parker, and she's listening

00:35:31.410 --> 00:35:33.510
to a one of these cylinders.

00:35:33.510 --> 00:36:34.280
[Molly Neptune Parker
speaking in Passamaquoddy

00:36:34.280 --> 00:37:35.040
and English while
listening to recording]

00:37:35.040 --> 00:37:36.460
&gt;&gt; Jane Anderson: So you can
kind of get a sense of like,

00:37:36.460 --> 00:37:39.170
the difficulty of, like
this constant listening,

00:37:39.170 --> 00:37:43.210
trying to pick out words, make
sense of them and then trying

00:37:43.210 --> 00:37:46.000
to kind of work out what
that is as a sentence or...

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:48.550
and then what it is as
a song and, you know,

00:37:48.550 --> 00:37:52.310
we have these very, very limited
descriptions from Fewkes.

00:37:52.310 --> 00:37:54.830
I think this one is Peter Lacoot

00:37:54.830 --> 00:37:57.170
who actually Molly is a
direct [descendant] of,

00:37:57.170 --> 00:38:00.290
who actually is singing
what - well, first of all,

00:38:00.290 --> 00:38:02.070
he wasn't in the
record to start with.

00:38:02.070 --> 00:38:04.840
Kelly found that [out] and
we went through the notebooks

00:38:04.840 --> 00:38:07.030
of Fewkes and we found that
there was a tiny reference

00:38:07.030 --> 00:38:09.420
to him in there in
relationship to this song

00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:12.620
and then it's subsequently
titled "War Song".

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:14.690
And so then we're kind of
going, "What is a war song?

00:38:14.690 --> 00:38:15.990
It doesn't sound
like a war song.

00:38:15.990 --> 00:38:17.300
What does a war song
sound like?"

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:20.610
...kind of thinking through
what does a war song sound like.

00:38:20.610 --> 00:38:22.730
And then, as Molly was
starting to [listen]...

00:38:22.730 --> 00:38:25.550
so this also a two part process.

00:38:25.550 --> 00:38:28.030
First, there's listening to
the tiny little pieces of words

00:38:28.030 --> 00:38:33.490
and stitching them together
and then there's this part...

00:38:33.490 --> 00:38:36.640
&gt;&gt; Molly Neptune Parker:
So that's more than one.

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:40.020
Him and whoever...he didn't say.

00:38:40.020 --> 00:38:43.370
He said he was going to go
hunting and they were going

00:38:43.370 --> 00:38:47.610
to go hunting, not just him -
they were going to go hunting,

00:38:47.610 --> 00:38:52.380
and when they get to wherever
their hunting place is,

00:38:52.380 --> 00:38:55.710
they said that they're going
to...they built a place

00:38:55.710 --> 00:38:59.240
to stay - they must have
built some kind of a shelter.

00:38:59.240 --> 00:39:01.940
And then he started ...

00:39:01.940 --> 00:39:04.700
now, I don't know when
he started the story,

00:39:04.700 --> 00:39:09.170
whether it was during, maybe
like dinner or something

00:39:09.170 --> 00:39:11.650
or on the way when
they were gathering,

00:39:11.650 --> 00:39:13.520
depending on how many
people they were,

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:15.980
because they usually
tell stories when there's

00:39:15.980 --> 00:39:21.230
at least a handful of people
and they always went hunting

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:26.800
by groups, not just
by themselves.

00:39:26.800 --> 00:39:28.500
So that's all I can tell.

00:39:28.500 --> 00:39:31.450
But there, what bothers
me is one word

00:39:31.450 --> 00:39:33.720
that he used [Passamaquoddy
word]

00:39:33.720 --> 00:39:38.370
and I think that's what he said.

00:39:38.370 --> 00:39:39.670
Yeah.

00:39:39.670 --> 00:39:41.720
&gt;&gt; Jane Anderson:
So you can see ...

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:44.160
then there's adding the
larger cultural context

00:39:44.160 --> 00:39:46.140
of what kind of, what
would they be speaking,

00:39:46.140 --> 00:39:48.920
when would they be saying
this, what does this mean

00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:52.470
within the larger context of
the Passamaquoddy tribe itself

00:39:52.470 --> 00:39:56.580
and so what we have as a
tiny record called "War Song"

00:39:56.580 --> 00:40:00.390
that Fewkes wrote down
is immeasurably increased

00:40:00.390 --> 00:40:04.210
when communities are part of
listening and adding this rich,

00:40:04.210 --> 00:40:06.720
rich data to kind
of what we have.

00:40:06.720 --> 00:40:09.620
And this is happening,
you know, in 2018

00:40:09.620 --> 00:40:11.740
and these recordings
are from 1890.

00:40:11.740 --> 00:40:14.090
So that kind of work
takes a really long time,

00:40:14.090 --> 00:40:15.990
but it's incredibly valuable.

00:40:15.990 --> 00:40:18.700
The one key part I want to
tell you about this project

00:40:18.700 --> 00:40:21.240
which I think is very important,
and just before handing

00:40:21.240 --> 00:40:24.540
over to Kim, is that as we've
been doing this work together,

00:40:24.540 --> 00:40:26.410
we've been creating
a parallel site

00:40:26.410 --> 00:40:30.120
which is the Passamaquoddy
Mukurtu site, which is where all

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:32.420
of this material that
we've been gathering lives

00:40:32.420 --> 00:40:34.580
and it's full of Passamaquoddy.

00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:38.430
It's all the different kinds
of rich textual analysis,

00:40:38.430 --> 00:40:40.260
understanding, interpretation

00:40:40.260 --> 00:40:41.620
that each community
that will add ...

00:40:41.620 --> 00:40:43.500
[that] the Passamaquoddy
community has been adding

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:44.990
as we go through each song.

00:40:44.990 --> 00:40:47.170
And that just becomes enormous.

00:40:47.170 --> 00:40:48.650
And so we've been building

00:40:48.650 --> 00:40:52.380
that into Passamaquoddy's own
Mukurtu site for it to live

00:40:52.380 --> 00:40:54.780
as another kind of record,
another kind of document,

00:40:54.780 --> 00:40:56.780
another kind of place
that is really

00:40:56.780 --> 00:40:59.180
for Passamaquoddy
interpretation.

00:40:59.180 --> 00:41:00.480
And so we have these kind

00:41:00.480 --> 00:41:02.650
of two different sites
now for this material.

00:41:02.650 --> 00:41:04.660
We have the AFC record

00:41:04.660 --> 00:41:06.880
which tells a very
particular kind of story.

00:41:06.880 --> 00:41:09.820
We also have the AFC record
pointing back to the authority

00:41:09.820 --> 00:41:12.580
of the Passamaquoddy community,
which is where authority

00:41:12.580 --> 00:41:15.040
over this material
really does lie.

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:23.160
And with that, I'm going
to hand it over to Kim.

